Operators:
General Rules of Operators:
* Types of operators:
  - Equality
  - Assignment
  - Mathematical
  - Logical
-------------
Assignment and Math Operators:
int intValue;
int intValue = 10;
                |
        Simple assignment

Assignment and simple math
int newValue = intValue + 5;
int newValue = intValue - 5;
int newValue = intValue * 5;
int newValue = intValue / 5;
int newValue = intValue % 5;
-------------------
int intValue = 10;
                |
            Initial value
Incrementing and decrementing
intValue ++;
intValue --;

Other assignments:
intValue += 5;
intValue -= 5;
intValue *= 5;
intValue /= 5;
--------------------
Postfix vs. Prefix Incrementing:
int intValue = 10;
                |
            Initial value
Postfix:
System.out.println(intValue ++); output: 10, new value: 11
System.out.println(++ intValue); output: 11, new value: 11
-----------------
Equality Operators:
Equality
if(this == that){
  System.out.println("They match!");
}

Inequality
if (this != that){// bang operator
  System.out.println("No match!");
}
-------------------------
Comparing Values:
Operator      Purpose
--------      --------
>             Greater than
<             Less than
>=            Greater than or equal
<=            Less than or equal
instanceof    Class membership

Example:
String s = "Hello";
if (s instanceof java.lang.String){
  System.out.println("s is a String");
}
------------
Comparing Strings
- Strings can't be compare using equality operator
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";
if(s1.equals(s2)){
  System.out.println("They match!");
}
else {
  System.out.println("No match!");
}
Output: They match!
---------------
Logical Operators:
Operator    Purpose
--------    -------
&&          And
||          Or
?:          Ternary (short-hand for if-then)

Example:
String s = condition ? trueValue : falseValue;
--------------
There are other operators called bit wise operators.
For more details check Java Documentation.
